Load the data¶

Here I load the three edgelistes and the nodelist.

I use "fread" to load the edgelist, because they are formatted as textfiles.

In [2]:
advice <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SDS-AAU/M2-2019/master/notebooks/assignments/assignment_1/data/Krack-High-Tec-edgelist-Advice.txt")
friendship <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SDS-AAU/M2-2019/master/notebooks/assignments/assignment_1/data/Krack-High-Tec-edgelist-Friendship.txt")
report_to <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SDS-AAU/M2-2019/master/notebooks/assignments/assignment_1/data/Krack-High-Tec-edgelist-ReportsTo.txt")

nodes <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SDS-AAU/M2-2019/master/notebooks/assignments/assignment_1/data/Krack-High-Tec-Attributes.csv")

1. Create a network¶

The three text matrices does not have coloumn names and therefor I add this using "colnames". This is maybe a bit unneccesary, but I like that the coloumnnames has a meaning ;-)

In [0]:
colnames(advice) <- c("ID", "alter", "presence")
colnames(friendship) <- c("ID", "alter", "presence")
colnames(report_to) <- c("ID", "alter", "presence")

Now I only want the edgelistes to contain edges that has 1 in presence, for example if there are are advice between to ID's (managers), then presence is 1. Else I would just get the same edges for alle three edgelist.

In [0]:
advice <- advice %>%
  filter(presence == 1)

friendship <- friendship %>%
  filter(presence == 1)

report_to <- report_to %>%
  filter(presence == 1)

1.1. Generate network objects¶

Here I start by loading the three different type of edges (advice, friendship, report to) into isolated networks.

In [0]:
g_advice <- graph_from_data_frame(d = advice, directed = TRUE, vertices = nodes)
g_friendship <- graph_from_data_frame(d = friendship, directed = TRUE, vertices = nodes)
g_report_to <- graph_from_data_frame(d = report_to, directed = TRUE, vertices = nodes)
In [0]:
g_advice <- g_advice %>%
  as_tbl_graph() %E>%
  mutate(type = "advice")

g_friendship <- g_friendship %>%
  as_tbl_graph() %E>%
  mutate(type = "friendship")

g_report_to <- g_report_to %>%
  as_tbl_graph() %E>%
  mutate(type = "report to")

2. Analysis¶

2.A. Network level characteristics¶

Density:

Here I use the "edge_density" function in the three edgelistes.

In [9]:
edge_density(g_advice)
edge_density(g_friendship)
edge_density(g_report_to)
0.452380952380952
0.242857142857143
0.0476190476190476

45,24% seek advice of possible connections in the network.

24,29% seek friendship of possible connections in the network.

They report to 4,76% of possible connections in the network.

Are the employees generally more likely to be in a friendship or advice-seeking relationship?

Yes, indeed. This makes sence, because of course the managers does not report to as many colleagues as they have friends- or advice relationship with.

In [10]:
transitivity(g_advice, type = "global")
transitivity(g_friendship, type = "global")
transitivity(g_report_to, type = "global")
0.734508816120907
0.471494607087827
0

Are friends of your friends also your friends?

Yes, to some extent (transitivity = 0.47). So some friends of your friends, is also your friends.

In [11]:
reciprocity(g_advice)
reciprocity(g_friendship)
reciprocity(g_report_to)
0.473684210526316
0.450980392156863
0

Are relationships like friendship and advice giving usually reciprocal?

If you look advice or have a friendship with a employee, they are also more likely to seek advice or have a friendship with you.

If you report to one, then they dont also report to you, which of course makes sence, because the person you report to is likely your manager.

2.B: Node level characteristics¶

Adding centrality degree to the three network graphs.

Here I add centrality degree to each network and I set the mode to "in", because I want the edge that comes in to the node, fx who get advice, who get friends and who are reported to.

In [0]:
g_advice <- g_advice %N>%
  mutate(centrality_dgr_out_advice = centrality_degree(mode = "out")) 
# I set mode = "out", because I consider advice relationship, that you give out advices. 

g_friendship <- g_friendship %N>%
  mutate(centrality_dgr_in_friendship = centrality_degree(mode = "in"))

g_report_to <- g_report_to %N>%
  mutate(centrality_dgr_in_report_to = centrality_degree(mode = "in"))

Who is the most wanted friend?

Here I print the head of the friend network as tibble and arrange it with descending centrality degree (so I get the person with highest friends in the top).

2.C. Relational Characteristics¶

Are managers from the same 1. department, or on the same 2. hirarchy, 3. age, or 4. tenuere more likely to become friends or give advice? (hint: assortiativity related)

1. Are managers from the same department more likely to become friends or give advice?

In [21]:
assortativity(g_friendship, V(g_friendship)$DEPT, directed = TRUE)
0.151157711410702

So managers are not so much likely to become friends with managers from same department.

In [22]:
assortativity(g_advice, V(g_advice)$DEPT, directed = TRUE)
0.107587088130058

Apparently managers doesnt give advice to so many in their own department, which is might a bit surprising.

2. Are managers from the same hirarchy more likely to become friends or give advice?

In [23]:
assortativity(g_friendship, V(g_friendship)$LEVEL, directed = TRUE)
0.259244657047721

So the managers are in a certain extent more likely to become friends at same hirarchy/LEVEL as them self, but still not so much.

In [24]:
assortativity(g_advice, V(g_advice)$LEVEL, directed = TRUE)
0.0553974479997201

Managers are much likely not to give managers at same hirarchy advice, which makes sence, that the managers probably give advice to employees at a lower hirarchy/level.

3. Are managers from the same age more likely to become friends or give advice?

In [25]:
assortativity(g_friendship, V(g_friendship)$AGE, directed = TRUE)
0.10028705775003

This is a bit surprising, that managers with the same age are not much more likely to become friends, where I would expect it to be much higher. But that just conclude that the managers are friends with different ages.

Maybe this coefficent can be caused that the age interval is not that wide.

In [26]:
assortativity(g_advice, V(g_advice)$AGE, directed = TRUE)
0.0387598006439393

Are friends more likely to give each others advice?

In [27]:
assortativity(g_advice, V(g_friendship)$centrality_dgr_in_friendship, directed = TRUE)
-0.0881102077099041

Not at all. So the managers wont give their friends advices.

3. Aggregated Networks¶

3.1. Aggregated advice network¶

I start by creating a new node list, that only contain the departments as nodes (= 5 nodes)

In [0]:
nodes_agg <- nodes %>%
  group_by(DEPT) %>%
  summarize(ID = n()) # I summarize so I only get a row for each department 
                      # the fact that I summarize by size of ID is not important.
In [93]:
nodes_agg
A tibble: 5 × 2
DEPTID
<dbl><int>
01
15
28
33
44

I create "nodes4join" as new dataframe, because I need this to left_join the ID for both "ID"(from) and "alter" (to) in the aggregated edgelist.

Here I only select ID and DEPT, because I dont need the other attributes.

In [0]:
nodes4join <- nodes %>%
  select(ID, DEPT)

Now I use "left_join" to get the DEPT number for both the "ID"(from) and "alter"(to) edges.

In [0]:
g_advice_agg <- advice %>%
  left_join(nodes4join, by = c("ID" = "ID")) %>%
  left_join(nodes4join, by = c("alter" = "ID"))
In [100]:
head(g_advice_agg)

IDalterpresenceDEPT.xDEPT.y
<dbl><dbl><int><dbl><dbl>

116144

121141

I rearrange the the coloumn order in the edgelist, because I need the DEPT.x (from) and DEPT.y (to) as edges and therefor to be first in the edgelist.

In [0]:
g_advice_agg <- g_advice_agg[c("DEPT.x", "DEPT.y", "ID", "alter", "presence")]

Now I transform the edgelist from dataframe to a graph object.

In [0]:
g_advice_agg <- graph_from_data_frame(d = g_advice_agg, directed = TRUE, vertices = nodes_agg)
In [103]:
plot(g_advice_agg)

In the plot, we can see that department 2 has alot of advice relationships, and department 0 (the CEO) has nearly none.

Now I will do the same as in part 3.1, just with the friendship network.

nodes_agg_f2 <- nodes %>%

g_friendship_agg <- friendship %>%

g_friendship_agg <- g_friendship_agg[c("DEPT.x", "DEPT.y", "ID", "alter", "presence")]

We can see in the plot, that department 0 (CEO) has 3 friends from department 1 and 2, but he doesnt see them as his/her friend.

Below here, I make the same plot, just where the node/vertex size is the degree of the friendship, where department 1,2 and 4 seem to be around equal popular across departmens, where department 3 has a bit lower degree.

plot(g_friendship_agg,
     vertex.size = 1+ sqrt(degree(g_friendship_agg, mode = "in")))
